00:03:31.780 --> 00:03:35.250
to charge you more and my Aunt
Rose would always say they have

00:03:35.250 --> 00:03:36.710
to charge you more in restaurants

00:03:36.710 --> 00:03:39.060
because they give you
such large portions.

00:03:39.060 --> 00:03:42.090
And they carried on this
argument for at least 60 years

00:03:42.090 --> 00:03:45.930 position:56%
that I was aware of and are probably
still arguing about it in heaven

00:03:45.930 --> 00:03:50.340
and even tragically after Uncle Ron
lost his vocal chords he would just

00:03:50.340 --> 00:03:52.750
say it in a high voice.

00:03:52.750 --> 00:03:55.550
They charge you, they give you
big portions because they want

00:03:55.550 --> 00:03:57.490
to charge you more, Rose.

00:03:57.490 --> 00:03:58.790
And she would come back at him.

00:03:58.790 --> 00:04:03.320
Every, every marriage like my
parents are devoted to food.

00:04:03.320 --> 00:04:07.010 position:56%
My mother, some of you may have read
I wrote a piece about cooking bread

00:04:07.010 --> 00:04:09.390
with my mother a couple
of years ago.

00:04:09.390 --> 00:04:11.420
It's not in the book, it's
not in The Table Comes First,

00:04:11.420 --> 00:04:14.830
but I'll put it in some
other book someday.

00:04:14.830 --> 00:04:16.740
And that was where we sort

00:04:16.740 --> 00:04:20.020
of discovered each other
was in the kitchen.

00:04:20.020 --> 00:04:23.490
My mother taught me how
to cook when I was a boy.

00:04:23.490 --> 00:04:28.480
I had 5 sisters if you can imagine,
and but she it was more important

00:04:28.480 --> 00:04:32.010
for the boys in the family to
learn to cook than the girls.

00:04:32.010 --> 00:04:36.010
So I learned to cook with my mother
and she's a fantastic cook, but she

00:04:36.010 --> 00:04:39.550
and my father have had the
same quarrel for as long

00:04:39.550 --> 00:04:41.220
as I can remember and that is

00:04:41.220 --> 00:04:43.760
about how many desserts
she is serving him.

00:04:43.760 --> 00:04:47.630
They have just celebrated their
60th wedding anniversary too

00:04:47.630 --> 00:04:49.230
and they are still
having the same quarrel.

00:04:49.230 --> 00:04:52.900
He says, Myrna, please don't give
me 3 desserts tonight and she does

00:04:52.900 --> 00:04:56.980
and then they just go right back
into the same thing the next night.

00:04:56.980 --> 00:05:02.620
I've been married for a little
while and my wife, Martha,

00:05:02.620 --> 00:05:06.270
and I have always had
the same argument,

00:05:06.270 --> 00:05:09.240
but our argument doesn't turn
around why they charge your more

00:05:09.240 --> 00:05:11.720
in restaurants or about questions

00:05:11.720 --> 00:05:14.150
of being given an over
abundance of food.

00:05:14.150 --> 00:05:19.020
Our argument is always about
one subject and it's about,

00:05:19.020 --> 00:05:21.770
some of you I'm sure have
had this argument too it's

00:05:21.770 --> 00:05:25.970
about rare and well-done meat.

00:05:25.970 --> 00:05:29.550
I come from a rare family
and my wife, Martha,

00:05:29.550 --> 00:05:34.430
who is of Icelandic descent, comes
from a very well-done family.

00:05:34.430 --> 00:05:38.890
[Laughter] And when you're
first courting someone,

00:05:38.890 --> 00:05:41.270
when you're first going out
with them and you're first going

00:05:41.270 --> 00:05:42.570
to restaurants with them

00:05:42.570 --> 00:05:47.210
and you don't quite
believe what you're hearing.

00:05:47.210 --> 00:05:48.510
You don't.

00:05:48.510 --> 00:05:54.000
When somebody says well-done on a
first date, you assume it's a joke.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.360
[Laughter] You assume
it's an affectation

00:05:56.360 --> 00:05:58.080
that someone is putting on.

00:05:58.080 --> 00:06:00.670
Beautiful girl and she's saying she
wants something well-done you just

00:06:00.670 --> 00:06:02.920 position:56%
assume she doesn't really mean that.

00:06:02.920 --> 00:06:05.880
She's just saying that because
she thinks it's compelling,

00:06:05.880 --> 00:06:07.290
it's winning.

00:06:07.290 --> 00:06:09.750
And then you go and you meet
her family and you discover

00:06:09.750 --> 00:06:15.170
that there are entire families,
clans, races of the well-done.

00:06:15.170 --> 00:06:17.470
And it's totally shocking to you.

00:06:17.470 --> 00:06:22.750
And I would go for a cookout in
her, at her family's little house

00:06:22.750 --> 00:06:26.790
in the suburbs of Montreal
where I grew up, met her,

00:06:26.790 --> 00:06:29.990
and her father would have
a hamburger on the grill

00:06:29.990 --> 00:06:35.960
and he would leave it there and
leave it there and leave it there

00:06:35.960 --> 00:06:40.100
and days were going by and
nobody would remove this

00:06:40.100 --> 00:06:43.910
and that's the way they liked
it because that mouth taste

00:06:43.910 --> 00:06:47.190
for well-done was a moral
taste in that family.

00:06:47.190 --> 00:06:50.540
It showed your distance
from your peasant roots

00:06:50.540 --> 00:06:52.240
and showed your distance
from the farm.

00:06:52.240 --> 00:06:54.990
They all came from families
of Icelandic farmers

00:06:54.990 --> 00:06:59.640
and that showed how far you'd come
from actually knowing the animal

00:06:59.640 --> 00:07:03.260
on a first-name basis because
it had been totally transformed

00:07:03.260 --> 00:07:06.300
into a bloodless object
at the end of it.

00:07:06.300 --> 00:07:10.050
My family on the other hand
was a very rare family exactly

00:07:10.050 --> 00:07:13.470
because for them it was a form

00:07:13.470 --> 00:07:17.080
of rejecting the taste
of their parents, right?

00:07:17.080 --> 00:07:20.210
Because they, I come from
a Jewish family obviously

00:07:20.210 --> 00:07:25.620
and their parents liked highly
koshered overcooked meat.

00:07:25.620 --> 00:07:28.020
When my great grandmother
would have you over for dinner,

00:07:28.020 --> 00:07:29.480
she would really have
you over for dinner.

00:07:29.480 --> 00:07:31.220
You would sit in the kitchen
and she would put food

00:07:31.220 --> 00:07:34.010
on your plate and then
leave the room.

00:07:35.020 --> 00:07:36.800
It was always hugely well-done.

00:07:36.800 --> 00:07:40.640
So my parents took on
the manner of the rare.

00:07:40.640 --> 00:07:42.520 position:56%
They liked anything that was bloody.

00:07:42.520 --> 00:07:46.490
It was a sign of their
assimilation into Europe,

00:07:46.490 --> 00:07:51.630
their osmosis into France,
their having an entirely new set

00:07:51.630 --> 00:07:56.440
of Bohemian and transgressive
values that included the power

00:07:56.440 --> 00:08:01.790
and the imagery of spurting
blood from your dinner.

00:08:03.140 --> 00:08:10.330
So this was a very deep quarrel,
very deep difference that Martha

00:08:10.330 --> 00:08:14.800 position:56%
and I took through life and you know
as it is when you have those kinds

00:08:14.800 --> 00:08:19.450
of tastes, you don't begin by
crediting that they're serious

00:08:19.450 --> 00:08:23.040
and then you're always sure that
the other person can reform.

00:08:23.040 --> 00:08:26.300
You're always sure that the
other person will change,

00:08:26.300 --> 00:08:29.470
and I was always sure
that if only I was cooking

00:08:29.470 --> 00:08:31.930
for her she would get better.

00:08:31.930 --> 00:08:34.950
And we got married and moved
to New York and I discovered

00:08:34.950 --> 00:08:37.650
that she was never
going to get better.

00:08:37.650 --> 00:08:40.250
She always liked things well-done.

00:08:40.250 --> 00:08:45.610
So then we had children and it
carried on, and we became a kind

00:08:45.610 --> 00:08:51.750
of family rift in as much as she
enlisted the children on her side

00:08:51.750 --> 00:08:55.860
of this divide, and I realized,
of course, after a certain time

00:08:55.860 --> 00:08:58.850
as I'm sure all of you have
realized since I raised the subject

00:08:58.850 --> 00:09:01.650
that essentially what's
involved in questions of rare

00:09:01.650 --> 00:09:05.760
and well-done is sexual rejection.

00:09:08.850 --> 00:09:11.510
[Laughter] That's obviously
what underlies it.

00:09:11.510 --> 00:09:15.530
One offers your wife something that
is pink and bloody and engorged

00:09:15.530 --> 00:09:21.010
and she says no and the
content couldn't be clearer,

00:09:21.010 --> 00:09:23.680
the moral content of that choice.

00:09:23.680 --> 00:09:31.410
But one day not too long ago I was,
it was actually a while ago now

00:09:31.410 --> 00:09:35.230
that I think about it because
the kids small, I was doing tuna.

00:09:35.230 --> 00:09:38.120
I was doing tuna au Poivre,
you know, where you do tuna

00:09:38.120 --> 00:09:42.160
in the same way the French do steak
au Poivre, it's a delicious thing,

00:09:42.160 --> 00:09:43.930
and of course, as all of you

00:09:43.930 --> 00:09:49.210
in this hall will agree tuna
can only be served rare.

00:09:49.210 --> 00:09:53.440
[Laughter] Tuna that is not served
rare is not tuna it is tuna fish.

00:09:53.440 --> 00:10:00.200
[Laughter] And you recall tuna fish
a totally different gustatory world

00:10:00.200 --> 00:10:01.500
than tuna, right?

00:10:01.500 --> 00:10:04.100
It comes in a can and you
slice it on a diagonal,

00:10:04.100 --> 00:10:07.410
on toast with mayonnaise.

00:10:07.410 --> 00:10:10.140
Tuna has got to be cooked rare
so I did my tuna au Poivre

00:10:10.140 --> 00:10:15.940 position:56%
and I served it rare and my wife
cut into it and I could see the look

00:10:15.940 --> 00:10:20.950 position:56%
of dismay on her face and I could
see our beautiful children mirroring

00:10:20.950 --> 00:10:27.720
the look of dismay on her face,
and it cut me to the quick.

00:10:27.720 --> 00:10:34.450
It involved sexual rejection,
familial sides taking,

00:10:34.450 --> 00:10:38.280
a belief somehow that my
understanding of everything

00:10:38.280 --> 00:10:42.510
that tuna should be was inadequate
to the measure of their appetites.

00:10:42.510 --> 00:10:44.630
It was a disaster.

00:10:44.630 --> 00:10:48.810
And I did what I have never done
