00:42:43.720 --> 00:42:47.100
First of all I should say that my
family, the four of us, we go in

00:42:47.100 --> 00:42:51.190
and out of spasmodic vegetarianism,
you know, everybody kind of looks

00:42:51.190 --> 00:42:55.240
and said, you know, we really
shouldn't for the reasons your wife

00:42:55.240 --> 00:42:59.580
for ethical reasons we should
become ethical vegetarians and one

00:42:59.580 --> 00:43:02.450
of other the kids bangs
their, his or her first,

00:43:02.450 --> 00:43:05.450
and says I'm an ethical
vegetarian now.

00:43:05.450 --> 00:43:08.920
And then it fades after about
two weeks and they go back

00:43:08.920 --> 00:43:10.690
and I realize it's sort
of the equivalent for sort

00:43:10.690 --> 00:43:15.170
of Manhattan metropolitan
people of finding Jesus

00:43:15.170 --> 00:43:16.580
and then losing Jesus
again, you know?

00:43:16.580 --> 00:43:19.420
You find him and then you
lose him and then you go back

00:43:19.420 --> 00:43:22.180
and you find him again,
and we treat vegetarianism

00:43:22.180 --> 00:43:25.060
in that same hyper
spiritualized way.

00:43:25.060 --> 00:43:30.580
The whole question I have
complicated feelings.

00:43:30.580 --> 00:43:33.740
One of my favorite French saying is
that grown up people should be able

00:43:33.740 --> 00:43:38.660
to count to two meaning that you
rarely resolve a moral question

00:43:38.660 --> 00:43:41.460
with one category or
one commandment.

00:43:41.460 --> 00:43:44.160
It usually takes some development.

00:43:44.160 --> 00:43:46.930
I [inaudible] evangelical in this
book and in all of my writing

00:43:46.930 --> 00:43:49.600
and in my own personal
practice about the importance

00:43:49.600 --> 00:43:55.230
of the local market, the
green market, farmers,

00:43:55.230 --> 00:44:00.430
dinner served at a
table cooked by a parent

00:44:00.430 --> 00:44:03.380
or by a kid I deeply
believe in those things.

00:44:03.380 --> 00:44:06.410
I believe that that really
is the sustainability

00:44:06.410 --> 00:44:11.340
of civilization depends
on dinner, it much begins

00:44:11.340 --> 00:44:13.690
at dinner as Lord Byron said.

00:44:13.690 --> 00:44:15.820
Much depends on dinner
I beg your pardon,

00:44:15.820 --> 00:44:18.950 position:56%
and I believe those things are vital
and central and it's hard for me

00:44:18.950 --> 00:44:23.610
to conceptualize a rich,
not only rich family life

00:44:23.610 --> 00:44:29.060
but a rich civilization that
doesn't have the consistent

00:44:29.060 --> 00:44:32.710
and traditional rituals
of food at its core.

00:44:32.710 --> 00:44:34.980
At the same time that
counting to two, right,

00:44:34.980 --> 00:44:37.540
at the same time I
would be a terrible snob

00:44:37.540 --> 00:44:42.090 position:56%
and horribly unrealistic if I didn't
recognize that the fast food culture

00:44:42.090 --> 00:44:44.880
that you have described
has grown up not simply

00:44:44.880 --> 00:44:48.730
as a shoddy moral preference
but in response

00:44:48.730 --> 00:44:51.860
to the huge unimaginable pressures

00:44:51.860 --> 00:44:55.750
of daily life in a
capitalist society.

00:44:55.750 --> 00:44:59.360
So I would never want to be
morally punitive about people

00:44:59.360 --> 00:45:02.220
who have a different set
of rituals than I do.

00:45:02.220 --> 00:45:05.680 position:56%
And I think that's one of the tricks
in a pluralist country is you have

00:45:05.680 --> 00:45:09.130
to be evangelical about your
values without being moralistic

00:45:09.130 --> 00:45:11.020 position:56%
about their absence in other people.

00:45:11.020 --> 00:45:14.510
That's a complicated two step,
but I think it's an important one.

00:45:14.510 --> 00:45:18.040
[ Applause ]

00:45:18.040 --> 00:45:20.380
Broadly applicable I would say.

00:45:20.380 --> 00:45:25.080
So, I try and keep both
things I mind as I do.

00:45:25.080 --> 00:45:30.180
I think that it's remarkable when
you look around to see the degree

00:45:30.180 --> 00:45:33.170
to which, you know, that's the
salad and McDonald's, right?

00:45:33.170 --> 00:45:37.420
To see the degree to which the
values of that were regarded

00:45:37.420 --> 00:45:41.550
as extremely [inaudible]
elitists used that horrible word.

00:45:41.550 --> 00:45:43.910
Thirty years ago I think
of my friend, Alice Waters,

00:45:43.910 --> 00:45:47.500
about whom I have a chapter
the originator of Chez Panisse

00:45:47.500 --> 00:45:50.480
in Berkeley and one of the first
people to bring these values

00:45:50.480 --> 00:45:53.800 position:56%
in a very aggressive way to America.

00:45:53.800 --> 00:45:57.170
And she, actually when I
was with her in France once

00:45:57.170 --> 00:46:00.100
and I said has your daughter
ever been to McDonald's?

00:46:00.100 --> 00:46:01.540 position:56%
And what would you say if she asked?

00:46:01.540 --> 00:46:05.090
She said, oh, I would simply say I
would prefer not to become involved

00:46:05.090 --> 00:46:06.490
in that kind of activity.

00:46:06.490 --> 00:46:08.420
[Laughter] Which I
thought was like going

00:46:08.420 --> 00:46:11.360
to a brothel, you know,
or something.

00:46:11.360 --> 00:46:16.670
Values that were elitist when Alice
first spouts them 50 years ago,

00:46:16.670 --> 00:46:19.920
40 years ago, are now commonplace
and you see them everywhere.

00:46:19.920 --> 00:46:23.620 position:56%
You see them even in, you know, Pret
A Monjay [phonetic], or some places

00:46:23.620 --> 00:46:26.160
like that, fast food places
that have those values.

00:46:26.160 --> 00:46:29.150
So I think that we should
never apologize for believing

00:46:29.150 --> 00:46:34.800
in those things, but we should
never enforce them in any way

00:46:34.800 --> 00:46:37.620
and we should always have a
little bit of modesty in our minds

00:46:37.620 --> 00:46:41.320
because we know that whatever
the good food rules are

00:46:41.320 --> 00:46:45.510
of our time will look ridiculous
50 years hence and we know

00:46:45.510 --> 00:46:47.330
that because the good rules

00:46:47.330 --> 00:46:50.900
of 50 years past look
ridiculous to us in lots of ways.

00:46:50.900 --> 00:46:54.650
What counted as good food
then now looks more dubious.

00:46:54.650 --> 00:46:56.300
So I try to keep both
things in mind.

00:46:56.300 --> 00:47:00.490 position:56%
In fact at one point in this book, I
explain and you don't get many books

00:47:00.490 --> 00:47:05.500
like this, that I give you the
secret of life, the secret of life,

00:47:05.500 --> 00:47:08.670
and it's right in the middle
of the third chapter actually.

00:47:08.670 --> 00:47:10.830
I shouldn't tell you, you'd have
to buy it and you'll get the secret

00:47:10.830 --> 00:47:15.380
of life, but basically it makes
sense same point in a different way

00:47:15.380 --> 00:47:19.670
that the secret of life is having
enough passion about your values

00:47:19.670 --> 00:47:23.320
to live them fully and enough
irony about your values

00:47:23.320 --> 00:47:25.200
to view them skeptically.

00:47:25.200 --> 00:47:27.930
I'll take one last question
and then I have to go.

00:47:27.930 --> 00:47:31.300
&gt;&gt; Do you ever go to
dinner with Calvin Trillin

00:47:31.300 --> 00:47:34.650
and exchange food philosophies?

00:47:34.650 --> 00:47:36.970
